<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-698-437  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 698 437.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Spectrum  Nov 1990 v27 n11 p78(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The case for CASE tools. (computer-aided software engineering)(Focus Report: Engineering Software) (buyers guide)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Software today is part of almost every electronic system beingengineered.andP;  The advent of the microprocessor brought software inas a standard part of most electronic products.andP;  Embedded softwareuses code that is invisible to the user, yet gives the productfunctionality.andP;  Computer-aided software engineering (CASE) todaymeans computer-aided systems engineering.andP;  Concurrent engineeringis the objective for hardware and software designers,manufacturing engineers, and logistics and maintenance personnelto perform project tasks in parallel.andP;  CASE uses a top-downapproach to creating software: the modern software developmentproject starts with a project/product planning phase, followed byrequirements/design analysis and software design phases.andO;Twenty-two CASE packages are listed with product name,manufacturer, price, platform, operating system, tool function,activities supported, methodology and general comments.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer-Aided Software EngineeringSoftware DesignMethodsEmbedded SystemsDirectoriesSoftware PackagesProgram Development Tools.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Representative computer-aided software engineering (CASE)packages. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>